{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479944"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:34:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:34:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20997"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20997"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.61,0.02,0.25,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100052"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13872"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20997"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82444"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"5825"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"13336"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44239"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100052"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 6-week-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with her parents for investigation of a fever. She was born at term with no complications and has been developing normally. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. The medical team needs to perform venepuncture for blood tests, and her parents are anxious about the pain she might experience during the procedure and ask about pain management options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She is alert and responsive with normal tone and reflexes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate approach to using sweet solution for procedural analgesia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apply to the venepuncture site prior to needle insertion","Administer directly to the tongue two minutes before the procedure","Administer via nasogastric tube five minutes before the procedure","Sweet solutions provide no significant analgesic benefit for infants","Mix with formula and feed immediately after the procedure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESweet solutions (typically 24% sucrose or 30% glucose) are effective for reducing procedural pain in infants up to 12 months of age. They work by stimulating taste receptors on the tongue, which triggers an endogenous opioid response. This mechanism provides mild analgesia suitable for brief painful procedures such as immunisations, blood tests, and minor interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering directly to the tongue two minutes before the procedure\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct method. This timing allows sufficient time for the endogenous opioid system to be activated before the painful stimulus occurs. The solution should be administered directly onto the anterior portion of the tongue where taste receptors are concentrated. Pre-packed products are available, including\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETootSweet 24% Sucrose Solution by MedTel\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESucrose Oral Solution 24% by Phebra\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESweet-Ease Natural by Philips\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplying to the venepuncture site\u003C/strong\u003E prior to needle insertion would not be effective as the analgesic mechanism of sweet solutions is orally mediated through taste receptors, not through topical application.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering via nasogastric tube\u003C/strong\u003E five minutes before the procedure would bypass the oral taste receptors that are necessary to trigger the endogenous opioid response. The analgesic effect of sweet solutions is dependent on taste receptor stimulation in the mouth, not on gastrointestinal absorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Esweet solutions provide no significant analgesic benefit for infants\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Multiple systematic reviews have demonstrated that sweet solutions significantly reduce pain scores and crying time during brief painful procedures in infants. This is well-established in the literature and incorporated into many clinical practice guidelines for infant pain management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixing with formula and feeding\u003C/strong\u003E immediately after the procedure would not provide any pre-procedural analgesia. Sweet solutions are intended to be used prophylactically before the painful stimulus, not as a treatment after pain has occurred. Additionally, diluting the sweet solution in formula would reduce its effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to sweet solutions, other pain management strategies for infant procedures include breastfeeding during the procedure, skin-to-skin contact, distraction techniques, and proper positioning. It\u0027s important to note that sweet solutions are contraindicated in infants with known fructose or sucrose intolerance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sweet solutions (sucrose or glucose) provide mild analgesia for brief painful procedures in infants through stimulation of endogenous opioid release.","Sweet solutions should be administered 2 minutes before the painful procedure to allow time for endogenous opioid release.","Sweet solutions are contraindicated in infants with fructose or sucrose intolerance."],"references":["RACGP Handbook of Non-Drug Interventions: Sweet solutions: procedural pain in infants (up to 12 months of age) Accessed at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/handi/a-z/s/sweet-solutions-procedural-pain-in-infants-up-to-1","Harrison D, Stevens B, Bueno M, Yamada J, Adams-Webber T, Beyene J, et al. Efficacy of sweet solutions for analgesia in infants between 1 and 12 months of age: a systematic review. Archives of Disease in Childhood.2010; 95(6):406\u201313.","Stevens B, Yamada J, Lee GY, Ohlsson A. Sucrose for analgesia in newborn infants undergoing painful procedures. Cochrane Database Syst Rev 2013;1:CD001069"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82444"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20997"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82444"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T21:32:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-26T06:52:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13872"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100052"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","